#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:11
msgid "Troubleshooting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:15
msgid ""
"Since this information may be updated regularly, please ensure you are "
"viewing the most `up-to-date version <https://numpy.org/devdocs/user/"
"troubleshooting-importerror.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:20
msgid "ImportError"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:22
msgid ""
"In certain cases a failed installation or setup issue can cause you to see "
"the following error message::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:25
msgid ""
"IMPORTANT: PLEASE READ THIS FOR ADVICE ON HOW TO SOLVE THIS ISSUE!\n"
"\n"
"Importing the numpy c-extensions failed. This error can happen for\n"
"different reasons, often due to issues with your setup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:30
msgid "The error also has additional information to help you troubleshoot:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:32
msgid "Your Python version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:33
msgid "Your NumPy version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:35
msgid ""
"Please check both of these carefully to see if they are what you expect. You "
"may need to check your ``PATH`` or ``PYTHONPATH`` environment variables (see "
"`Check Environment Variables`_ below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:39
msgid ""
"The following sections list commonly reported issues depending on your "
"setup. If you have an issue/solution that you think should appear please "
"open a NumPy issue so that it will be added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:43
msgid ""
"There are a few commonly reported issues depending on your system/setup. If "
"none of the following tips help you, please be sure to note the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:46
msgid "how you installed Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:47
msgid "how you installed NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:48
msgid "your operating system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:49
msgid "whether or not you have multiple versions of Python installed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:50
msgid ""
"if you built from source, your compiler versions and ideally a build log"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:52
msgid "when investigating further and asking for support."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:56
msgid "Using Python from ``conda`` (Anaconda)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:58
msgid ""
"Please make sure that you have activated your conda environment. See also "
"the `conda user-guide <https://docs.conda.io/projects/conda/en/latest/user-"
"guide/tasks/manage-environments.html#activating-an-environment>`_. If you "
"use an external editor/development environment it will have to be set up "
"correctly.  See below for solutions for some common setups."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:64
msgid "Using PyCharm with Anaconda Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:66
msgid ""
"There are fairly common issues when using PyCharm together with Anaconda, "
"please see the `PyCharm support <https://www.jetbrains.com/help/pycharm/"
"conda-support-creating-conda-virtual-environment.html>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:70
msgid "Using VS Code with Anaconda Python (or environments)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:72
msgid ""
"A commonly reported issue is related to the environment activation within "
"VSCode. Please see the `VSCode support <https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/"
"python/environments>`_ for information on how to correctly set up VSCode "
"with virtual environments or conda."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:78
msgid "Using Eclipse/PyDev with Anaconda Python (or environments)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:80
msgid ""
"Please see the `Anaconda Documentation <https://docs.anaconda.com/working-"
"with-conda/ide-tutorials/eclipse-pydev/>`_ on how to properly configure "
"Eclipse/PyDev to use Anaconda Python with specific conda environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:87
msgid "Debug build on Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:89
msgid ""
"Rather than building your project in ``DEBUG`` mode on windows, try building "
"in ``RELEASE`` mode with debug symbols and no optimization. Full ``DEBUG`` "
"mode on windows changes the names of the DLLs python expects to find, so if "
"you wish to truly work in ``DEBUG`` mode you will need to recompile the "
"entire stack of python modules you work with including NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:98
msgid "All setups"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:100
msgid ""
"Occasionally there may be simple issues with old or bad installations of "
"NumPy. In this case you may just try to uninstall and reinstall NumPy. Make "
"sure that NumPy is not found after uninstalling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:106
msgid "Development setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:108
msgid ""
"If you are using a development setup, make sure to run ``git clean -xdf`` to "
"delete all files not under version control (be careful not to lose any "
"modifications you made, e.g. ``site.cfg``). In many cases files from old "
"builds may lead to incorrect builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:115
msgid "Check environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:117
msgid ""
"In general how to set and check your environment variables depends on your "
"system. If you can open a correct python shell, you can also run the "
"following in python::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:121
msgid ""
"import os\n"
"print(\"PYTHONPATH:\", os.environ.get('PYTHONPATH'))\n"
"print(\"PATH:\", os.environ.get('PATH'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:125
msgid ""
"This may mainly help you if you are not running the python and/or NumPy "
"version you are expecting to run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:130
msgid "Downstream ImportError, AttributeError or C-API/ABI incompatibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:132
msgid "If you see a message such as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:134
msgid ""
"A module that was compiled using NumPy 1.x cannot be run in\n"
"NumPy 2.0.0 as it may crash. To support both 1.x and 2.x\n"
"versions of NumPy, modules must be compiled with NumPy 2.0.\n"
"Some module may need to rebuild instead e.g. with 'pybind11>=2.12'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:139
msgid "either as an ``ImportError`` or with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:141
msgid "AttributeError: _ARRAY_API not found"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:143
msgid "or other errors such as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:145
msgid ""
"RuntimeError: module compiled against API version v1 but this version of "
"numpy is v2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:147
msgid "or when a package implemented with Cython::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:149
msgid ""
"ValueError: numpy.dtype size changed, may indicate binary incompatibility. "
"Expected 96 from C header, got 88 from PyObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:151
msgid ""
"This means that a package depending on NumPy was build in a way that is not "
"compatible with the NumPy version found. If this error is due to a recent "
"upgrade to NumPy 2, the easiest solution may be to simply downgrade NumPy to "
"``'numpy<2'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:156
msgid ""
"To understand the cause, search the traceback (from the back) to find the "
"first line that isn't inside NumPy to see which package has the "
"incompatibility. Note your NumPy version and the version of the incompatible "
"package to help you find the best solution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:161
msgid "There can be various reasons for the incompatibility:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:163
msgid ""
"You have recently upgraded NumPy, most likely to NumPy 2, and the other "
"module now also needs to be upgraded.  (NumPy 2 was released in June 2024.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:166
msgid ""
"You have version constraints and ``pip`` may have installed a combination of "
"incompatible packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:169
msgid ""
"You have compiled locally or have copied a compiled extension from elsewhere "
"(which is, in general, a bad idea)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:172
msgid "The best solution will usually be to upgrade the failing package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:174
msgid ""
"If you installed it for example through ``pip``, try upgrading it with ``pip "
"install package_name --upgrade``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:177
msgid ""
"If it is your own package or it is build locally, you need recompiled for "
"the new NumPy version (for details see :ref:`depending_on_numpy`). It may be "
"that a reinstall of the package is sufficient to fix it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:181
msgid ""
"When these steps fail, you should inform the package maintainers since they "
"probably need to make a new, compatible, release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:184
msgid ""
"However, upgrading may not always be possible because a compatible version "
"does not yet exist or cannot be installed for other reasons.  In that case:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:187
msgid "Install a compatible NumPy version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:189
msgid ""
"Try downgrading NumPy with ``pip install 'numpy<2'`` (NumPy 2 was released "
"in June 2024)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:191
msgid ""
"If your NumPy version is old, you can try upgrading it for example with "
"``pip install numpy --upgrade``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:194
msgid ""
"Add additional version pins to the failing package to help ``pip`` resolve "
"compatible versions of NumPy and the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:200
msgid "Segfaults or crashes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:202
msgid ""
"NumPy tries to use advanced CPU features (SIMD) to speed up operations. If "
"you are getting an \"illegal instruction\" error or a segfault, one cause "
"could be that the environment claims it can support one or more of these "
"features but actually cannot. This can happen inside a docker image or a VM "
"(qemu, VMWare, ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:208
msgid ""
"You can use the output of ``np.show_runtime()`` to show which SIMD features "
"are detected. For instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:211
msgid ""
">>> np.show_runtime()\n"
"WARNING: `threadpoolctl` not found in system! Install it by `pip install \\\n"
"threadpoolctl`. Once installed, try `np.show_runtime` again for more "
"detailed\n"
"build information\n"
"[{'simd_extensions': {'baseline': ['SSE', 'SSE2', 'SSE3'],\n"
"                      'found': ['SSSE3',\n"
"                                'SSE41',\n"
"                                'POPCNT',\n"
"                                'SSE42',\n"
"                                'AVX',\n"
"                                'F16C',\n"
"                                'FMA3',\n"
"                                'AVX2'],\n"
"                      'not_found': ['AVX512F',\n"
"                                    'AVX512CD',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_KNL',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_KNM',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_SKX',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_CLX',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_CNL',\n"
"                                    'AVX512_ICL']}}]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:233
msgid ""
"In this case, it shows AVX2 and FMA3 under the ``found`` section, so you can "
"try disabling them by setting ``NPY_DISABLE_CPU_FEATURES=\"AVX2,FMA3\"`` in "
"your environment before running python (for cmd.exe on windows)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:237
msgid ""
">SET NPY_DISABLE_CPU_FEATURES=\"AVX2,FMA3\"\n"
">python <myprogram.py>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:240
msgid ""
"By installing threadpoolctl ``np.show_runtime()`` will show additional "
"information::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:242
msgid ""
"...\n"
"{'architecture': 'Zen',\n"
"  'filepath': '/tmp/venv3/lib/python3.9/site-packages/numpy.libs/"
"libopenblas64_p-r0-15028c96.3.21.so',\n"
"  'internal_api': 'openblas',\n"
"  'num_threads': 24,\n"
"  'prefix': 'libopenblas',\n"
"  'threading_layer': 'pthreads',\n"
"  'user_api': 'blas',\n"
"  'version': '0.3.21'}]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:252
msgid ""
"If you use the wheel from PyPI, it contains code from the OpenBLAS project "
"to speed up matrix operations. This code too can try to use SIMD "
"instructions. It has a different mechanism for choosing which to use, based "
"on a CPU architecture, You can override this architecture by setting "
"``OPENBLAS_CORETYPE``: a minimal value for ``x86_64`` is "
"``OPENBLAS_CORETYPE=Haswell``.  This too needs to be set before running your "
"python (this time for posix)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/troubleshooting-importerror.rst:260
msgid "$ OPENBLAS_CORETYPE=Haswell python <myprogram.py>"
msgstr ""
